'''Ōtoshi Kotohira Shrine''' (大歳金刀比羅神社) is a {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto|qq=}} shrine located in {{ill|Taka Town|ja|多可町|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taka Town|qq=}}, Naka-ku, Hyōgo Prefecture.

== Overview ==

Historically referred to as '''Ōtoshi Shrine''', it originally enshrined {{ill|Amenomahitotsu|ja|天目一箇神|1=Ame-no-Mahitotsu-no-Mikoto|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amenomahitotsu|13=User:Immanuelle/Ame-no-Mahitotsu-no-Mikoto|qq=}}, the deity of blacksmithing. The establishment date is unknown; however, the shrine's land records from the {{ill|Enpō|ja|延宝|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enpō|qq=}} period (Enpō 5) mention ownership of nine tan and 20 bu of {{ill|Shinden|ja|神田|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinden|qq=}} dating back to land surveys in the {{ill|Keichō|ja|慶長|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Keichō|qq=}} era, suggesting an earlier origin. In {{ill|1795|ja|寛政6th year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1795|qq=}} (Kansei 6), Fujii Magorōemon of Kajiyama Village invited the spirit of {{ill|Kotohira-gū|ja|金刀比羅宮|1=Kotohira-gū|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotohira-gū|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotohira-gū|qq=}} from {{ill|Sanuki Province|ja|讃岐国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sanuki Province|qq=}} to cure illnesses, establishing a {{ill|Sessha|ja|摂社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sessha|qq=}} within the grounds of Ōtoshi Shrine.<ref name=p687/>

After the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji Restoration|qq=}}, the shrine was designated as a {{ill|Sonsha|ja|村社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sonsha|qq=}} in 1874 (Meiji 7) under the {{ill|Modern shrine Ranking system|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|1=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Modern shrine Ranking system|13=User:Immanuelle/Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=}}. In 1911 (Meiji 44), due to decay, the main hall of Ōtoshi Shrine was dismantled, and the main hall of Kotohira Shrine, reconstructed in 1881 (Meiji 18), was relocated to the site. The shrine was renamed '''Ōtoshi Kotohira Shrine'''.<ref name=p687/>

== Shrine Buildings ==

* '''Main Hall'''
: The main hall follows an {{ill|Irimoya-zukuri|ja|入母屋造|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Irimoya-zukuri|qq=}} structure with {{ill|Hira-iri|ja|平入|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hira-iri|qq=}} roofing and {{ill|Hiwadabuki|ja|檜皮葺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiwadabuki|qq=}}. Its dimensions are three ken at the front and two ken at the side. It features {{ill|Chidori Hafu|ja|千鳥破風|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chidori Hafu|qq=}} and a {{ill|Karaha Hafu|ja|唐破風|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Karaha Hafu|qq=}}, with eaves extending one ken. The structure includes triple balustrades and a raised floor. Richly adorned with carvings, it serves as an important example of local shrine architecture from the 19th to early 20th centuries.<ref name=p688/>

* '''Former Worship Hall'''
: This is the original worship hall of Ōtoshi Shrine, relocated and repurposed. It has an irimoya-zukuri structure, a long-floor plan, and {{ill|Sangawara Buki|ja|桟瓦葺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sangawara Buki|qq=}} roofing. The size is three ken at the front and two ken at the side. Though altered by later repairs, it is believed to have been built in the early 19th century, providing insight into earlier shrine architecture.<ref name=p688/>

<gallery>
File:Otoshi-konpira - Honden.jpg|Main Hall
</gallery>

== Sub-Shrines ==

* Daijingū Shrine
* {{ill|Amenomahitotsu Shrine|ja|天目一神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amenomahitotsu Shrine|qq=}}
* {{ill|Yasaka Inari Shrine|ja|八坂稲荷神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yasaka Inari Shrine|qq=}}
* Kitahari Gokoku Shrine

== Festivals ==

* '''festival (November 23)'''
: Known as one of the "Three Great Festivals of Harima Province," alongside the festivals of {{ill|Itatehyōzu Shrine|ja|射楯兵主神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Itatehyōzu Shrine|qq=}} in Himeji and {{ill|Sumiyoshi Shrine (Kasai City)|ja|住吉神社 (加西市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumiyoshi Shrine (Kasai City)|qq=}} in Kitahari.<ref>Other interpretations of the "Three Great Festivals" include those of {{ill|Saho Shrine|ja|佐保神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saho Shrine|qq=}}, {{ill|Ōmiya Hachiman Shrine (Miki City)|ja|大宮八幡宮 (三木市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmiya Hachiman Shrine (Miki City)|qq=}}, {{ill|Takasago Shrine|ja|高砂神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takasago Shrine|qq=}}, {{ill|Munetsa Yakujin Shrine|ja|宗佐厄神八幡神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Munetsa Yakujin Shrine|qq=}}, and {{ill|Matsubara Hachiman Shrine|ja|松原八幡神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsubara Hachiman Shrine|qq=}}.</ref> In the past, the festival attracted up to 100,000 visitors. During the operation of the {{ill|Kajiyama Line|ja|鍛冶屋線|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kajiyama Line|qq=}} (discontinued in 1990), trains were extended to five or six cars to accommodate the influx of pilgrims.

