== Festivals ==

* '''festival (November 23)'''
: Known as one of the "Three Great Festivals of Harima Province," alongside the festivals of [[:en:Itatehyōzu Shrine|Itatehyōzu Shrine]] in Himeji and {{ill|Sumiyoshi Shrine (Kasai City)|ja|住吉神社 (加西市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumiyoshi Shrine (Kasai City)|qq=|1=Sumiyoshi Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11381861}} in Kitahari.<ref>Other interpretations of the "Three Great Festivals" include those of {{ill|Saho Shrine|ja|佐保神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saho Shrine|qq=}}, [[:en:Ōmiya Hachiman Shrine (Hyōgo)|Ōmiya Hachiman Shrine (Miki City)]], {{ill|Takasago Shrine|ja|高砂神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takasago Shrine|qq=}}, {{ill|Munetsa Yakujin Shrine|ja|宗佐厄神八幡神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Munetsa Yakujin Shrine|qq=|1=Sousayakujin-hachiman Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11451841}}, and {{ill|Matsubara Hachiman Shrine|ja|松原八幡神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsubara Hachiman Shrine|qq=|1=Matsubara Hachiman Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11529360}}.</ref> In the past, the festival attracted up to 100,000 visitors. During the operation of the [[:en:Kajiya Line|Kajiyama Line]] (discontinued in 1990), trains were extended to five or six cars to accommodate the influx of pilgrims.

